## The mechanism

When you meet someone, you are not seeing “a person” neutrally.

You are seeing:

**F1**: their body, voice, face, clothes, movement.

**F1E**: your nervous system’s state while perceiving them.

**F2**: your personal associations, fears, desires, memories, attachment patterns.

**F3**: collective archetypes and social symbols: stranger, friend, threat, lover, teacher, rival, boss, outsider, insider, masculine, feminine, cool person, dangerous person, high-status person.

**F1S**: the actual relation forming between you.

So F1S is not just “society.”

F1S is **the live rendering of relation**.

## Why it changes so fast with new people

Because the prior is thin.

With a new person, you have little individual data.

So your system leans heavily on:

appearance

accent

tone

body language

style

context

status signals

similarity to previous people

archetypes

vibe

your current nervous state

That means every new bit of information has high weight.

One joke changes the rendering.

One kind look changes the rendering.

One awkward pause changes the rendering.

One shared interest changes the rendering.

One moment of rejection changes the rendering.

The person rapidly transforms from:

“stranger”

to “safe”

to “interesting”

to “threatening”

to “attractive”

to “one of us”

to “not my type”

to “possible friend”

to “authority”

to “rival”

That is Bayesian social rendering.

## Why old friends feel stable

With an old friend, the prior is thick.

You have hundreds or thousands of stored interactions.

So one weird moment does not update the model much.

They can be quiet and you do not immediately think they hate you.

They can disagree and the relation survives.

They can be tired and you do not re-render them as hostile.

The relation has inertia.

So:

> new person = high update rate.
> old friend = low update rate.

That is why social perception is unstable at first and stable later.

