## 1. Enactivism: “a world appears through interaction”

Enactivism says cognition is not a brain passively representing a ready-made world. It arises through interaction between organism and environment. The key idea is that organisms **enact** a world through sensorimotor activity, rather than simply receiving information. ([Wikipedia][1])

This already fits your basic metaphysics:

> world = rendered experience under conditions.

The social version is even closer. Hanne De Jaegher and Ezequiel Di Paolo’s idea of **participatory sense-making** says that social cognition is not just “I model you inside my head.” The interaction process itself can become partially autonomous and generate meaning between people. ([Wikipedia][1])

That is basically your F1S:

> the relation itself becomes a world-making process.

So the strongest research phrase for your model is:

> **participatory sense-making.**

In your terms:

> F1S is participatory sense-making rendered as social world.

---

## 2. Relational sociology: society is not a container; society is relation

Relational sociology explicitly rejects the idea that individuals or “society” are pre-given substances. It argues that transactions, interactions, social ties, and conversations are the central stuff of social life. One summary even says society is not a space containing relations; society **is relation**. ([Wikipedia][2])

This is almost exactly the Marx/Smith correction to your model.

Your old model risked:

> individual first, relation second.

Relational sociology says:

> relation is not added to individuals; relation helps constitute individuals.

So F1S is not just “me plus you.”

F1S is the field in which “me” and “you” become what they are to each other.

This also supports your intuition that when you enter a job interview, a friendship group, a date, a family dinner, or a spiritual community, you enter a **different world**.

Not physically different.

Relationally different.

---

## 3. Active inference: social perception is Bayesian updating

Active inference and predictive processing give you the computational mechanism.

The basic idea is that agents act and perceive through generative models: they predict what is happening, update from sensory evidence, and act to reduce uncertainty. Recent work even formalizes active inference with Bayesian updating, perception, planning, and free-energy minimization across levels of an agent’s generative model. ([arXiv][3])

Applied socially, this means:

> I perceive you through a model of who you are, what you intend, how you see me, and what relation is forming between us.

There is also active-inference work on empathy as **self-other model transformation**. A 2026 paper models empathy in active inference agents and finds that empathic perspective-taking can support cooperation, synchronized behavior, recovery after ruptures, and apology-forgiveness-like dynamics. ([arXiv][4])

That maps beautifully to intimacy.

In your terms:

> Intimacy is not just emotion.
> Intimacy is mutual self-other model updating under trust.

A useful formula:

> **F1S = Bayesian social inference + embodied co-regulation + symbolic role-rendering.**

---

## 4. Impression formation: new people update fast, old friends update slowly

Your “new person vs old friend” point is directly supported by social psychology.

Research on first impressions says people form mental images of others quickly, based on cues like appearance, accent, posture, voice, culture, language, gender, economic status, and context. First impressions can form within milliseconds, and early cues can have long-term effects on how a person is remembered. ([Wikipedia][5])

Impression formation research also talks about **primacy effects**, confirmation bias, and revision. Early information often anchors the model, but strong disconfirming evidence can update it. ([Wikipedia][6])

That is exactly your Bayesian intuition:

> new person = thin prior, high update rate.
> old friend = thick prior, low update rate.

With a new person, every cue matters.

With an old friend, the relation has inertia.

So your F1S model has a clean cognitive-science translation:

> Social perception is impression formation under uncertainty, updated by interaction.

---

## 5. Interpersonal neurobiology and co-regulation: bodies render together

Your F1E → F1S bridge is also supported.

Interpersonal neurobiology frames mind as embodied and relational, with social interactions shaping neural connections through feedback loops. In this model, mind is not only inside one skull; it involves flows of energy and information within and between brains. ([Wikipedia][7])

Social baseline theory also says the brain assumes social proximity as a baseline condition. The presence of trusted others can reduce threat responses and help regulate emotion through risk distribution, load sharing, and capitalization. ([Wikipedia][8])

That supports your line:

> connection changes F1E.

A calm person can change the felt world.

A threatening person can change the felt world.

A trusted person can make F1 feel less hostile.

So intimacy is partly:

> nervous systems co-regulating inside a relational field.

Or:

> F1E shared through F1S.

---

## 6. Hyperscanning / second-person neuroscience: the relation is measurable

There is now a whole research area studying two or more brains during live interaction.

Hyperscanning is the method of recording brain activity from multiple people at once while they interact. Researchers developed this because studying one brain alone is limited for social interaction; one classic analogy says studying interaction by scanning only one person is like studying a synapse while observing only the presynaptic or postsynaptic neuron, but never both. ([Wikipedia][9])

This is strong support for your point that relation has its own dynamics.

The unit is not just:

> brain A
> brain B

The unit becomes:

> brain A ↔ interaction ↔ brain B

Recent dyadic neuroscience work even models joint neural activity from structured social interactions and tries to capture speaker-listener roles and behavioral metrics. ([arXiv][10])

In your language:

> F1S is not imaginary.
> It has behavioral, bodily, and neural correlates.

---

## 7. Recognition theory: the self needs relation to become itself

Hegel/Honneth-style recognition theory gives the philosophical/social version.

Recognition justice and Honneth’s work emphasize that subjectivity is constituted through intersubjective relationships, especially love, rights, and solidarity. Misrecognition, disrespect, humiliation, and non-recognition become sources of conflict. ([Wikipedia][11])

This maps directly to intimacy and alienation.

Recognition means:

> I appear to myself differently because of how I am received by you.

Misrecognition means:

> I am trapped in a false or degrading relational rendering.

This is exactly F1S.

The self is not just internally generated.

The self is socially mirrored, confirmed, denied, wounded, or liberated.

